“## Sample datan”, “n”, “In all of the demonstrations, we will use the same sample data set of $x,y$ values taken from three different trials. The sample data were numerically generated using the following hierarchical generative model.n”, “n”, “\begin{align}n”, “&n = (20, 25, 18)^\mathsf{T},\\[1em]n”, “&\theta = (3, 7)^\mathsf{T},\\[1em]n”, “&\mathsf{T} = \begin{pmatrix}1 & 0 \\ 0 & 16\end{pmatrix}, \\[1em]n”, “&\sigma = (2, 3)^\mathsf{T},\\[1em]n”, “&\rho = 0.6,\\[1em]n”, “&\mathsf{\Sigma} = \begin{pmatrix}\sigma_1^2 & \rho\sigma_1\sigma_2 \\ \rho\sigma_1\sigma_2 & \sigma_2^2\end{pmatrix}, \\[1em]n”, “&\theta_{1, i} \sim \text{Norm}(\theta, \mathsf{T}) \;\forall\,i\in\{1, 2, 3\},\\[1em]n”, “& \begin{pmatrix} x_{i, j} \\ y_{i,j} \end{pmatrix} \sim \text{Norm}(\theta_i, \mathsf{\Sigma})\;\forall\,i \in \{1, 2, 3\}, \; j \in \{1, \ldots, n_i \}. n”, “\end{align}n”, “n”, “Unless doing Bayesian modeling with Stan, for simplicity we will ignore the hierarchical nature of the data set. n”, “n”, “To get familiar with the data set, let’s load it in and take a look.”
